The Great Pyramid is three institutions in one structure: a public machine of kingship and spectacle, a hidden machine of death-accounting and soul adjudication, and a sealed machine of cosmic containment. It was built by the Solar Court of the Undivided Disk to contain the Black Sun Shard — a fragment of anti-light that consumed names, certainties, and memory, causing crop failure under clear skies, the dead rising in wrong lives, and households losing lineage knowledge. The founding sovereign Ramesses-of-the-First-Binding declared sunlight to be law made visible, fusing astronomical governance with containment ritual. Six construction eras produced the current layered structure: processional stateworks (broad plazas, lion gates, tribute halls), priestly infrastructure (oath halls, ink vaults, embalmer kilns), catacomb industrialization (mass interment sublevels, bound-dead labor), Tribunal Complex expansion (weighing halls, confession extraction chambers, archive vaults), Crown War sancta (militarized coronation spaces, beast rites), and Apex Seals (reverse-solar geometry retrofitting for near-failed containment). The Solar Court's five priestly offices — Dawn Liturgists, Ledger Priests, Embalmer Houses, Jackal Tribunal, and Seal College — became competing factions. The Jackal Tribunal's epistemic triage function: souls were weighted not only for moral worth but for civilizational risk, and memory that might destabilize succession or reveal containment practices was sealed, relocated, or ritual-burned. Three sentence classes: Interment (memory retained, body sealed), Service (memory compressed, spirit bound to labor), Correction (memory rewritten for political continuity). The Correction class was systematically abused in late dynastic periods. Ghosts in the lower halls speak in fragments because they are partially edited.

