Midgaard's relationship to the Great Pyramid is scholarly and commercial. City archives hold expedition charter records and trade documentation for goods of pyramid-complex provenance, including materials attested as originating from various pyramid-era layers. The pyramid's administrative technology — its system of ledger priests maintaining tribute records, census counts, and legal testimony in an integrated archive — is recognized by Midgaard archivists as a predecessor to their own civic record practices, though the theological overlay is alien to Midgaard's secular administrative tradition. Current Midgaard concern: pyramid-origin relics circulating in desert caravan markets require provenance documentation that verifies they are not Correction-class artifacts — materials whose inscriptions have been deliberately altered to support specific lineage claims. The Jackal Synod's presence throughout the pyramid complex means access to specific archive layers requires either Synod clearance (politically unacceptable) or force (logistically difficult). Midgaard's historical society has cataloged obelisk inscriptions from the Eastern Desert that cross-reference pyramid construction-era administrative records.

