Kowloon's Jade Magistracy holds the Great Pyramid's Ledger Priest function as an ancestral administrative parallel: tribute records, census counts, and legal testimony in one integrated archive, maintained by a professional scribal class with hereditary training. The Ledger Priest office is the direct institutional ancestor of the administrative traditions House Jien carried when founding Kowloon's covenant bureaucracy. The Correction sentence class — memory rewritten for political continuity — is the specific failure mode that Kowloon's covenant law most explicitly guards against: the Neon Covenant's witness-statement protocols include mandatory external verification requirements designed to prevent exactly the "adverse correction" that destabilized the late Solar Court. Kowloon tracks pyramid-origin materials entering Mafdet's harbor as a historical record concern: if Correction-class artifacts circulate into commercial markets, they can introduce false lineage documentation into otherwise reliable record systems.

